<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="105" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="105">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="105">
<taxonomicName class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella beitelii" order="Selaginellales" pageId="12" pageNumber="105" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="beitelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="105">Selaginella beitelii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was considered endemic to Sierra (Cerro) de la Neblina in Venezuela (
<bibRefCitation author="Smith, AR" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="21" pageNumber="114" pagination="249 - 273" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399539" refId="B24" refString="Smith, AR, 1990. Pteridophytes of the Venezuelan Guayana: New species. Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 77: 249 - 273, DOI: 10.2307/2399539" title="Pteridophytes of the Venezuelan Guayana: New species." url="10.2307/2399539" volume="77" year="1990">Smith 1990</bibRefCitation>
). It is now known from the Brazilian side of this mountain. It is terrestrial or epiphytic and characterized by having axillary rhizophores, median leaves broadly ovate to semicordate with the outer base prominently lobed and the inner base oblique, the margins narrowly hyaline (more so on inner ones) and denticulate, and the lamina abruptly tapering towards the apex, the lateral leaves broadly ovate to semicordate with the acroscopic half almost twice as wide as the basiscopic half, the acroscopic margin narrowly hyaline to greenish, the basiscopic margin greenish, and both margins denticulate to entire.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
